aVWhite House photo by Eric DraperEvery time I'm invited to this rostrum, I'm humbled by the privilege, and mindful of the history we've seen together.
p7
aVWe have gathered under this Capitol dome in moments of national mourning and national achievement.
p8
aVWe have served America through one of the most consequential periods of our history -- and it has been my honor to serve with you.
p9
aVIn a system of two parties, two chambers, and two elected branches, there will always be differences and debate.
p10
aVBut even tough debates can be conducted in a civil tone, and our differences cannot be allowed to harden into anger.
p11
aVTo confront the great issues before us, we must act in a spirit of goodwill and respect for one another -- and I will do my part.
p12
aVTonight the state of our Union is strong -- and together we will make it stronger.
p13
aV(Applause.)
p14
aVIn this decisive year, you and I will make choices that determine both the future and the character of our country.
p15
aVWe will choose to act confidently in pursuing the enemies of freedom -- or retreat from our duties in the hope of an easier life.
p16
aVWe will choose to build our prosperity by leading the world economy -- or shut ourselves off from trade and opportunity.
p17
aVIn a complex and challenging time, the road of isolationism and protectionism may seem broad and inviting -- yet it ends in danger and decline.
p18
aVThe only way to protect our people, the only way to secure the peace, the only way to control our destiny is by our leadership -- so the United States of America will continue to lead.
p19
aV(Applause.)
p20
aVAbroad, our nation is committed to an historic, long-term goal -- we seek the end of tyranny in our world.
p21
aVSome dismiss that goal as misguided idealism.
p22
aVIn reality, the future security of America depends on it.
p23
aVOn September the 11th, 2001, we found that problems originating in a failed and oppressive state 7,000 miles away could bring murder and destruction to our country.
p24
aVDictatorships shelter terrorists, and feed resentment and radicalism, and seek weapons of mass destruction.
p25
aVDemocracies replace resentment with hope, respect the rights of their citizens and their neighbors, and join the fight against terror.
p26
aVEvery step toward freedom in the world makes our country safer -- so we will act boldly in freedom's cause.
p27
aV(Applause.)
p28
aVFar from being a hopeless dream, the advance of freedom is the great story of our time.
p29
aVIn 1945, there were about two dozen lonely democracies in the world.
p30
aVToday, there are 122.
p31
aVAnd we're writing a new chapter in the story of self-government -- with women lining up to vote in Afghanistan, and millions of Iraqis marking their liberty with purple ink, and men and women from Lebanon to Egypt debating the rights of individuals and the necessity of freedom.
p32
aVAt the start of 2006, more than half the people of our world live in democratic nations.
p33
aVAnd we do not forget the other half -- in places like Syria and Burma, Zimbabwe, North Korea, and Iran -- because the demands of justice, and the peace of this world, require their freedom, as well.
p34
aV(Applause.)
