aVWhite House photo by Eric Draper The same is true of Iran, a nation now held hostage by a small clerical elite that is isolating and repressing its people.
p124
aVThe regime in that country sponsors terrorists in the Palestinian territories and in Lebanon -- and that must come to an end.
p125
aV(Applause.)
p126
aVThe Iranian government is defying the world with its nuclear ambitions, and the nations of the world must not permit the Iranian regime to gain nuclear weapons.
p127
aV(Applause.)
p128
aVAmerica will continue to rally the world to confront these threats.
p129
aVTonight, let me speak directly to the citizens of Iran: America respects you, and we respect your country.
p130
aVWe respect your right to choose your own future and win your own freedom.
p131
aVAnd our nation hopes one day to be the closest of friends with a free and democratic Iran.
p132
aV(Applause.)
p133
aVTo overcome dangers in our world, we must also take the offensive by encouraging economic progress, and fighting disease, and spreading hope in hopeless lands.
p134
aVIsolationism would not only tie our hands in fighting enemies, it would keep us from helping our friends in desperate need.
p135
aVWe show compassion abroad because Americans believe in the God-given dignity and worth of a villager with HIV/AIDS, or an infant with malaria, or a refugee fleeing genocide, or a young girl sold into slavery.
p136
aVWe also show compassion abroad because regions overwhelmed by poverty, corruption, and despair are sources of terrorism, and organized crime, and human trafficking, and the drug trade.
p137
aVIn recent years, you and I have taken unprecedented action to fight AIDS and malaria, expand the education of girls, and reward developing nations that are moving forward with economic and political reform.
p138
aVFor people everywhere, the United States is a partner for a better life.
p139
aVShort-changing these efforts would increase the suffering and chaos of our world, undercut our long-term security, and dull the conscience of our country.
p140
aVI urge members of Congress to serve the interests of America by showing the compassion of America.
p141
aVOur country must also remain on the offensive against terrorism here at home.
p142
aVThe enemy has not lost the desire or capability to attack us.
p143
aVFortunately, this nation has superb professionals in law enforcement, intelligence, the military, and homeland security.
p144
aVThese men and women are dedicating their lives, protecting us all, and they deserve our support and our thanks.
p145
aV(Applause.)
p146
aVThey also deserve the same tools they already use to fight drug trafficking and organized crime -- so I ask you to reauthorize the Patriot Act.
p147
aV(Applause.)
p148
aVIt is said that prior to the attacks of September the 11th, our government failed to connect the dots of the conspiracy.
p149
aVWe now know that two of the hijackers in the United States placed telephone calls to al Qaeda operatives overseas.
p150
aVBut we did not know about their plans until it was too late.
p151
aVSo to prevent another attack -- based on authority given to me by the Constitution and by statute -- I have authorized a terrorist surveillance program to aggressively pursue the international communications of suspected al Qaeda operatives and affiliates to and from America.
p152
aVPrevious Presidents have used the same constitutional authority I have, and federal courts have approved the use of that authority.
p153
aVAppropriate members of Congress have been kept informed.
p154
aVThe terrorist surveillance program has helped prevent terrorist attacks.
p155
aVIt remains essential to the security of America.
p156
aVIf there are people inside our country who are talking with al Qaeda, we want to know about it, because we will not sit back and wait to be hit again.
p157
aV(Applause.)
p158
aVIn all these areas -- from the disruption of terror networks, to victory in Iraq, to the spread of freedom and hope in troubled regions -- we need the support of our friends and allies.
p159
aVTo draw that support, we must always be clear in our principles and willing to act.
p160
aVThe only alternative to American leadership is a dramatically more dangerous and anxious world.
p161
aVYet we also choose to lead because it is a privilege to serve the values that gave us birth.
p162
aVAmerican leaders -- from Roosevelt to Truman to Kennedy to Reagan -- rejected isolation and retreat, because they knew that America is always more secure when freedom is on the march.
p163
aVOur own generation is in a long war against a determined enemy -- a war that will be fought by Presidents of both parties, who will need steady bipartisan support from the Congress.
p164
aVAnd tonight I ask for yours.
p165
aVTogether, let us protect our country, support the men and women who defend us, and lead this world toward freedom.
p166
aV(Applause.)
p167
aVHere at home, America also has a great opportunity: We will build the prosperity of our country by strengthening our economic leadership in the world.
p168
aVOur economy is healthy and vigorous, and growing faster than other major industrialized nations.
p169
aVIn the last two-and-a-half years, America has created 4.6 million new jobs -- more than Japan and the European Union combined.
p170
aV(Applause.)
p171
aVEven in the face of higher energy prices and natural disasters, the American people have turned in an economic performance that is the envy of the world.
p172
aVThe American economy is preeminent, but we cannot afford to be complacent.
p173
aVIn a dynamic world economy, we are seeing new competitors, like China and India, and this creates uncertainty, which makes it easier to feed people's fears.
p174
aVSo we're seeing some old temptations return.
p175
aVProtectionists want to escape competition, pretending that we can keep our high standard of living while walling off our economy.
p176
aVOthers say that the government needs to take a larger role in directing the economy, centralizing more power in Washington and increasing taxes.
p177
aVWe hear claims that immigrants are somehow bad for the economy -- even though this economy could not function without them.
p178
aV(Applause.)
p179
aVAll these are forms of economic retreat, and they lead in the same direction -- toward a stagnant and second-rate economy.
p180
aVTonight I will set out a better path: an agenda for a nation that competes with confidence; an agenda that will raise standards of living and generate new jobs.
p181
aVAmericans should not fear our economic future, because we intend to shape it.
p182
aVKeeping America competitive begins with keeping our economy growing.
p183
aVAnd our economy grows when Americans have more of their own money to spend, save, and invest.
p184
aVIn the last five years, the tax relief you passed has left $880 billion in the hands of American workers, investors, small businesses, and families -- and they have used it to help produce more than four years of uninterrupted economic growth.
p185
aV(Applause.)
p186
aVYet the tax relief is set to expire in the next few years.
p187
aVIf we do nothing, American families will face a massive tax increase they do not expect and will not welcome.
p188
aVBecause America needs more than a temporary expansion, we need more than temporary tax relief.
p189
aVI urge the Congress to act responsibly, and make the tax cuts permanent.
p190
aV(Applause.)
p191
aVKeeping America competitive requires us to be good stewards of tax dollars.
p192
aVEvery year of my presidency, we've reduced the growth of non-security discretionary spending, and last year you passed bills that cut this spending.
p193
aVThis year my budget will cut it again, and reduce or eliminate more than 140 programs that are performing poorly or not fulfilling essential priorities.
p194
aVBy passing these reforms, we will save the American taxpayer another $14 billion next year, and stay on track to cut the deficit in half by 2009.
p195
aV(Applause.)
p196
aVI am pleased that members of Congress are working on earmark reform, because the federal budget has too many special interest projects.
p197
aV(Applause.)
p198
aVAnd we can tackle this problem together, if you pass the line-item veto.
p199
aV(Applause.)
p200
aVWe must also confront the larger challenge of mandatory spending, or entitlements.
p201
aVThis year, the first of about 78 million baby boomers turn 60, including two of my Dad's favorite people -- me and President Clinton.
p202
aV(Laughter.)
p203
aVThis milestone is more than a personal crisis -- (laughter) -- it is a national challenge.
p204
aVThe retirement of the baby boom generation will put unprecedented strains on the federal government.
p205
aVBy 2030, spending for Social Security, Medicare and Medicaid alone will be almost 60 percent of the entire federal budget.
p206
aVAnd that will present future Congresses with impossible choices -- staggering tax increases, immense deficits, or deep cuts in every category of spending.
p207
aVCongress did not act last year on my proposal to save Social Security -- (applause) -- yet the rising cost of entitlements is a problem that is not going away.
p208
aV(Applause.)
p209
aVAnd every year we fail to act, the situation gets worse.
p210
aVSo tonight, I ask you to join me in creating a commission to examine the full impact of baby boom retirements on Social Security, Medicare, and Medicaid.
p211
aVThis commission should include members of Congress of both parties, and offer bipartisan solutions.
p212
aVWe need to put aside partisan politics and work together and get this problem solved.
p213
aV(Applause.)
p214
aVKeeping America competitive requires us to open more markets for all that Americans make and grow.
p215
aVOne out of every five factory jobs in America is related to global trade, and we want people everywhere to buy American.
p216
aVWith open markets and a level playing field, no one can out-produce or out-compete the American worker.
p217
aV(Applause.)
p218
aVKeeping America competitive requires an immigration system that upholds our laws, reflects our values, and serves the interests of our economy.
p219
aVOur nation needs orderly and secure borders.
p220
aV(Applause.)
p221
aVTo meet this goal, we must have stronger immigration enforcement and border protection.
p222
aV(Applause.)
p223
aVAnd we must have a rational, humane guest worker program that rejects amnesty, allows temporary jobs for people who seek them legally, and reduces smuggling and crime at the border.
p224
aV(Applause.)
p225
aVKeeping America competitive requires affordable health care.
p226
aV(Applause.)
p227
aVOur government has a responsibility to provide health care for the poor and the elderly, and we are meeting that responsibility.
p228
aV(Applause.)
p229
aVFor all Americans -- for all Americans, we must confront the rising cost of care, strengthen the doctor-patient relationship, and help people afford the insurance coverage they need.
p230
aV(Applause.)
p231
aVWe will make wider use of electronic records and other health information technology, to help control costs and reduce dangerous medical errors.
p232
aVWe will strengthen health savings accounts -- making sure individuals and small business employees can buy insurance with the same advantages that people working for big businesses now get.
p233
aV(Applause.)
p234
aVWe will do more to make this coverage portable, so workers can switch jobs without having to worry about losing their health insurance.
p235
aV(Applause.)
p236
aVAnd because lawsuits are driving many good doctors out of practice -- leaving women in nearly 1,500 American counties without a single OB/GYN -- I ask the Congress to pass medical liability reform this year.
p237
aV(Applause.)
p238
aVKeeping America competitive requires affordable energy.
p239
aVAnd here we have a serious problem: America is addicted to oil, which is often imported from unstable parts of the world.
p240
aVThe best way to break this addiction is through technology.
p241
aVSince 2001, we have spent nearly $10 billion to develop cleaner, cheaper, and more reliable alternative energy sources -- and we are on the threshold of incredible advances.
p242
aVSo tonight, I announce the Advanced Energy Initiative -- a 22-percent increase in clean-energy research -- at the Department of Energy, to push for breakthroughs in two vital areas.
p243
aVTo change how we power our homes and offices, we will invest more in zero-emission coal-fired plants, revolutionary solar and wind technologies, and clean, safe nuclear energy.
p244
aV(Applause.)
p245
aVWe must also change how we power our automobiles.
p246
aVWe will increase our research in better batteries for hybrid and electric cars, and in pollution-free cars that run on hydrogen.
p247
aVWe'll also fund additional research in cutting-edge methods of producing ethanol, not just from corn, but from wood chips and stalks, or switch grass.
p248
aVOur goal is to make this new kind of ethanol practical and competitive within six years.
p249
aV(Applause.)
p250
aVBreakthroughs on this and other new technologies will help us reach another great goal: to replace more than 75 percent of our oil imports from the Middle East by 2025.
p251
aV(Applause.)
p252
aVBy applying the talent and technology of America, this country can dramatically improve our environment, move beyond a petroleum-based economy, and make our dependence on Middle Eastern oil a thing of the past.
p253
aV(Applause.)
p254
aVAnd to keep America competitive, one commitment is necessary above all: We must continue to lead the world in human talent and creativity.
p255
aVOur greatest advantage in the world has always been our educated, hardworking, ambitious people -- and we're going to keep that edge.
p256
aVTonight I announce an American Competitiveness Initiative, to encourage innovation throughout our economy, and to give our nation's children a firm grounding in math and science.
p257
aV(Applause.)
p258
aVFirst, I propose to double the federal commitment to the most critical basic research programs in the physical sciences over the next 10 years.
p259
aVThis funding will support the work of America's most creative minds as they explore promising areas such as nanotechnology, supercomputing, and alternative energy sources.
p260
aVSecond, I propose to make permanent the research and development tax credit -- (applause) -- to encourage bolder private-sector initiatives in technology.
p261
aVWith more research in both the public and private sectors, we will improve our quality of life -- and ensure that America will lead the world in opportunity and innovation for decades to come.
p262
aV(Applause.)
p263
aVThird, we need to encourage children to take more math and science, and to make sure those courses are rigorous enough to compete with other nations.
p264
aVWe've made a good start in the early grades with the No Child Left Behind Act, which is raising standards and lifting test scores across our country.
p265
aVTonight I propose to train 70,000 high school teachers to lead advanced-placement courses in math and science, bring 30,000 math and science professionals to teach in classrooms, and give early help to students who struggle with math, so they have a better chance at good, high-wage jobs.
p266
aVIf we ensure that America's children succeed in life, they will ensure that America succeeds in the world.
p267
aV(Applause.)
p268
aVPreparing our nation to compete in the world is a goal that all of us can share.
p269
aVI urge you to support the American Competitiveness Initiative, and together we will show the world what the American people can achieve.
p270
aVAmerica is a great force for freedom and prosperity.
p271
aVYet our greatness is not measured in power or luxuries, but by who we are and how we treat one another.
p272
aVSo we strive to be a compassionate, decent, hopeful society.
p273
aVIn recent years, America has become a more hopeful nation.
p274
aVViolent crime rates have fallen to their lowest levels since the 1970s.
p275
aVWelfare cases have dropped by more than half over the past decade.
p276
aVDrug use among youth is down 19 percent since 2001.
p277
aVThere are fewer abortions in America than at any point in the last three decades, and the number of children born to teenage mothers has been falling for a dozen years in a row.
p278
aV(Applause.)
p279
aVThese gains are evidence of a quiet transformation -- a revolution of conscience, in which a rising generation is finding that a life of personal responsibility is a life of fulfillment.
p280
aVGovernment has played a role.
p281
aVWise policies, such as welfare reform and drug education and support for abstinence and adoption have made a difference in the character of our country.
p282
aVAnd everyone here tonight, Democrat and Republican, has a right to be proud of this record.
p283
aV(Applause.)
p284
aVYet many Americans, especially parents, still have deep concerns about the direction of our culture, and the health of our most basic institutions.
p285
aVThey're concerned about unethical conduct by public officials, and discouraged by activist courts that try to redefine marriage.
p286
aVThey worry about children in our society who need direction and love, and about fellow citizens still displaced by natural disaster, and about suffering caused by treatable diseases.
p287
aVAs we look at these challenges, we must never give in to the belief that America is in decline, or that our culture is doomed to unravel.
p288
aVThe American people know better than that.
p289
aVWe have proven the pessimists wrong before -- and we will do it again.
p290
aV(Applause.)
p291
